#week-title("Three", "The Fourfold Elemental Separation")

=== Core Teaching

After the long putrefaction, the water (including the Gur) is moved to the
distillation apparatus. The goal is to separate the water into four equal
fractions, each representing one of the four elements.

This is not a mechanical volume measurement alone; it requires attentive sensory
observation. The transitions between elements are subtle shifts in drop
formation, viscosity, and scent.

=== Practical Protocol: III. Elemental Separation

Collect four equal fractions (25% each) of the total volume:

1.  *Fire of Water:* The most volatile, sharp, and spiritualised fraction.
2.  *Air of Water:* Heavier, flatter in scent.
3.  *Water of Water (Phlegm):* The heavy, watery body.
4.  *Earth of Water:* Stop before the flask residue scorches.

The residue remaining is the *Concentrated Gur*. Scrape it out carefully and
dry gently (below 65°C). The seeds of life within it are destroyed above this
temperature.

=== Topics This Week

- Distillation as a diagnostic of the spirit
- The four elemental registers of water
- Observational markers: drop shape, viscosity, and scent shifts
- Drying the Gur: the 65°C non-negotiable limit

#inner-work[
  *The Language of Transitions*

  As you distil your water this week, pay extreme attention to the "moment of
  shift" between fractions. These subtle transitions map to the shifts in your
  own consciousness during meditation — where one state of mind gives way to the
  next.

  Record your observations of these physical and mental shifts in your journal.
